ublic institutions and local and national activistsDrawing on four decades of research, Bernard Spolsky presents an updated theory of language policy that starts with the individual speaker instead of the nation. In this book, he surveys the language practices, beliefs, and planning efforts of individuals, families, public and private institutions, local and national activists, advocates and managers, and nations. He examines the diversity of linguistic repertoires and the multiplicity of forces, linguistic and non-linguistic, which account for language shift and maintenance. By starting with the individual speaker and moving through the various levels and domains, Spolsky shows the many different policies with which a national government must compete and illustrates why national policy is so difficult. A definitive guide to the field, this is essential reading for policy makers, stakeholders, researchers, and students of language policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLanguage policy. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2021 Englishz978311075406308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2021z9783110753950oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107804060 cprintz978147448546340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147448548740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474485487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474485487/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075406-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Edu